                    "game-obj": "Traits",
                    "game-id": "651e06f09e5aea780d7c70a36ce5b1f2",
                    "text": "Vegetable creatures have the plant trait. They are distinct from normal plants. Magical effects with this trait manipulate or conjure plants or plant matter in some way. Effects that manipulate plants have no effect in an area with no plants.",
                    "classes": [
                        "creature_type"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "name": "Wood",
                    "type": "trait",
                    "edition": "remastered",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Player Core",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Player Core pg. 463",
                                "alt": "Player Core pg. 463",
                                "game-obj": "Sources",
                                "aonid": 216
                            },
                            "page": 463,
                            "errata": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "2.0",
                                "alt": "2.0",
                                "game-obj": "Sources",
                                "aonid": 216
                            }
                        }
                    ],
                    "game-obj": "Traits",
                    "game-id": "7c548a9e0a2647c082989720b3de0a87",
                    "text": "Effects with the wood trait conjure or manipulate wood. Those that manipulate wood have no effect in an area without wood. Creatures with this trait consist primarily of wood or have a connection to magical wood.  \n  \nThese planes consist of trees and other flora latticed in organic patterns. Wood planes are often perfectly constructed to match their desired purpose or environment but aren\u2019t usually outright hostile to visitors.",
                    "classes": [
                        "monsters"
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "family": {
                "name": "Arboreal",
                "type": "monster_family",
                "sections": [
                    {
                        "name": "Felled Arboreals",
                        "type": "section",
                        "text": "Arboreals have a great respect for dead members of their species. Their elaborate burial rituals involve laying the fallen arboreal down in a mossy bed in the center of a grove of saplings. The decomposing arboreal nourishes the saplings, ensuring the growth of a new generation of trees.",
                        "sources": [
                            {
                                "type": "source",
                                "name": "Monster Core",
                                "link": {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "name": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                                    "alt": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                                    "game-obj": "Sources",
                                    "aonid": 221
                                },
                                "page": 24,
                                "errata": {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "name": "1.1",
                                    "alt": "1.1",
                                    "game-obj": "Sources",
                                    "aonid": 221
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "Fungus Networks",
                        "type": "section",
                        "text": "Particularly old arboreal regents and other powerful arboreals can tap into the extensive network of fungus that connects the roots of all the trees in the forest. By doing so, the arboreal can learn of threats throughout the entire woodland, even from miles away.",
                        "sources": [
                            {
                                "type": "source",
                                "name": "Monster Core",
                                "link": {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "name": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                                    "alt": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                                    "game-obj": "Sources",
                                    "aonid": 221
                                },
                                "page": 24,
                                "errata": {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "name": "1.1",
                                    "alt": "1.1",
                                    "game-obj": "Sources",
                                    "aonid": 221
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "Late Bloomers",
                        "type": "section",
                        "text": "Though they grow faster than trees, arboreals take decades to reach maturity. They spend their early years rooted in place, developing an affinity with the flora of their homeland and attuning to its rhythms while adult arboreals keep a watchful eye on their progress. After their first century, young arboreals become more mobile, often apprenticing with senior arboreals in their territory as they learn to take up the mantle of forest guardians.",
                        "sources": [
                            {
                                "type": "source",
                                "name": "Monster Core",
                                "link": {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "name": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                                    "alt": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                                    "game-obj": "Sources",
                                    "aonid": 221
                                },
                                "page": 24,
                                "errata": {
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "name": "1.1",
                                    "alt": "1.1",
                                    "game-obj": "Sources",
                                    "aonid": 221
                                }
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ],
